                        "version": 0,
                        "content": "A client with Parkinson's disease has begun therapy with levodopa/carbidopa. The nurse determines that the client understands the action of the medication if he or she verbalizes that results may not be apparent for approximately how long?",
                        "subjectId": "ad5ab04c79144c0ea9b83385308c3b1d",
                        "difficultyIds": "a0f7d178f7b728b8bba7ef20ddeca62d",
                        "difficulty": "考试范围-Evaluating 评价",
                        "textAnalysis": "Rationale:\nSigns and symptoms of Parkinson's disease usually begin to resolve within approximately 2 to 3 weeks of starting therapy, although in some clients marked improvement may not be seen for up to 6 months. The client needs to understand this concept to aid in compliance with medication therapy.",
                        "id": "697ed61a70274505a9d3b32fa6984e84",
                        "mark": "0",
                        "collectionState": "0"
                    },
                    {
                        "optionList": [
                            {
                                "isRight": "0",
                                "userAnswer": "",
                                "isSelected": "0",
                                "id": "c04fddd72d7a40849fc22d190c4cc091",
                                "content": "Vitamin B6 will change perspiration and urine to a dark color, which may stain clothing."
                            },
                            {
                                "isRight": "1",
                                "userAnswer": "",
                                "isSelected": "0",
                                "id": "3745b151139a4da98e27e17eae4986c4",
                                "content": "Vitamin B6 reverses the effectiveness of the medication, meaning a higher dose is needed."
                            },
                            {
                                "isRight": "0",
                                "userAnswer": "",
                                "isSelected": "0",
                                "id": "1ab0cd10a90d4907892dce137985763c",
                                "content": "The medication competes with vitamin B6 for absorption in the intestine, blocking absorption."
                            },
                            {
                                "isRight": "0",
                                "userAnswer": "",
                                "isSelected": "0",
                                "id": "ef8ef4da822643959a56b7fc327515d4",
                                "content": "The two medications in combination will cause the blood sugar to drop, causing hypoglycemia."
                            }
                        ],
                        "extJson": {
                            "optionList": [
                                {
                                    "isRight": "0",
                                    "userAnswer": "",
                                    "isSelected": "0",
                                    "id": "c04fddd72d7a40849fc22d190c4cc091",
                                    "content": "Vitamin B6 will change perspiration and urine to a dark color, which may stain clothing."
                                },
                                {
                                    "isRight": "1",
                                    "userAnswer": "",
                                    "isSelected": "0",
                                    "id": "3745b151139a4da98e27e17eae4986c4",
                                    "content": "Vitamin B6 reverses the effectiveness of the medication, meaning a higher dose is needed."
                                },
                                {
                                    "isRight": "0",
                                    "userAnswer": "",
                                    "isSelected": "0",
                                    "id": "1ab0cd10a90d4907892dce137985763c",
                                    "content": "The medication competes with vitamin B6 for absorption in the intestine, blocking absorption."
                                },
                                {
                                    "isRight": "0",
                                    "userAnswer": "",
                                    "isSelected": "0",
                                    "id": "ef8ef4da822643959a56b7fc327515d4",
                                    "content": "The two medications in combination will cause the blood sugar to drop, causing hypoglycemia."
                                }
                            ]
